nutrientAnalysisDetails.labMethodDescription: Ethanol extraction along with dithiothreitol (DTT) reduction, followed by LC-MS/MS analysis
nutrientAnalysisDetails.labMethodOriginalDescription:
One gram of undried mushroom samples was weighed in 15 mL polypropylene tubes and kept on ice. To inhibit endogenous enzyme activities, 4 mL of ice-cold ethanol and 550 μL of a mixture of a protease inhibitor cocktail (ReadyShield® PIC0005) and 50 mM EDTA disodium salt in 100 mM ammonium bicarbonate buffer, pH 8.5 (1:10; v/v) was added to the mushroom samples. Samples were mixed by vortex. An internal standard of 200 μL of 100 μg/mL glutathione-(glycine-13C2, 15N) was added to the tubes, followed by adding 350 μL of 265 mg/mL dithiothreitol (DTT) prepared in 100 mM ammonium bicarbonate buffer, pH 8.5. After mixing samples by vortex, samples were incubated at 37°C for 2 h with continuous vigorous shaking. Two milliliters of ethanol were added to the samples, which were then mixed by vortex and centrifuged at 4,000 g at 4°C for 15 min. The supernatants were decanted into new 15 mL polypropylene tubes. The pellets were suspended in 7 mL of 75% ethanol by mixing with glass stirring rods and vortex. Samples were centrifuged with the above condition. The two supernatants were combined and mixed by inverting the tubes several times. An aliquot of 150 μL of combined supernatants was transferred to 1.5 mL microcentrifuge tubes and dried by speedvac. The dried samples were dissolved in 100 μL of pure water and then filtered with 0.2 μm polyethersulfone filter plates.  
Glutathione concentration was determined by liquid chromatography triple quadrupole mass spectrometer (Agilent 1260 Infinity II LC system with 6470 Triple Quadrupole LC-MS) using multiple reaction monitoring (MRM) analysis. Chromatographic separation was performed on an Agilent AdvanceBio Peptide Map (2.1 × 150 mm, 2.7 μm) analytical column with an AdvanceBio Peptide Map guard column (2.1 × 5 mm, 2.7 μm) at a flow rate of 0.3 mL/min. The mobile phase gradient composed of 0.1 % formic acid and 3% acetonitrile in water (v/v/v) (solvent A) and 0.1 % formic acid and 10% water in acetonitrile (v/v/v) (solvent B) was as follows: 0-16% B from 0-2 min; 16-100% B from 2-3 min; 100% B from 3-4.5 min; 100-0% B 4.5-5 min. The column was equilibrated with 100% A for 8 min before the next injection. MRM analysis was conducted in the positive mode with one transition as the quantifier and two transitions as qualifiers for the analyte and the internal standard. For glutathione, the quantifier was m/z 308.0 -> 179.0, and the qualifiers were m/z 308.0 -> 233.0 and m/z 308.0 -> 162.0. For glutathione-(glycine-13C2, 15N), the quantifier was m/z 311.0 -> 182.0, and the qualifiers were m/z 311.0 -> 165.0 and m/z 311.0 -> 84.0. Calibration standards of glutathione with a concentration range of 0.1-50 μg/mL and 2 μg/mL of internal standard were prepared in 20 mM DTT.

An internal standard of 200 μL of 100 μg/mL glutathione-(glycine-13C2, 15N) was added to the tubes, followed by adding 350 μL of 265 mg/mL dithiothreitol (DTT) prepared in 100 mM ammonium bicarbonate buffer, pH 8.5. After mixing samples by vortex, samples were incubated at 37°C for 2 h with continuous vigorous shaking. Two milliliters of ethanol were added to the samples, which were then mixed by vortex and centrifuged at 4,000 g at 4°C for 15 min. The supernatants were decanted into new 15 mL polypropylene tubes. The pellets were suspended in 7 mL of 75% ethanol by mixing with glass stirring rods and vortex. Samples were centrifuged with the above condition. The two supernatants were combined and mixed by inverting the tubes several times. An aliquot of 150 μL of combined supernatants was transferred to 1.5 mL microcentrifuge tubes and dried by speedvac. The dried samples were dissolved in 100 μL of pure water and then filtered with 0.2 μm polyethersulfone filter plates.  
Glutathione concentration was determined by liquid chromatography triple quadrupole mass spectrometer (Agilent 1260 Infinity II LC system with 6470 Triple Quadrupole LC-MS) using multiple reaction monitoring (MRM) analysis. Chromatographic separation was performed on an Agilent AdvanceBio Peptide Map (2.1 × 150 mm, 2.7 μm) analytical column with an AdvanceBio Peptide Map guard column (2.1 × 5 mm, 2.7 μm) at a flow rate of 0.3 mL/min. The mobile phase gradient composed of 0.1 % formic acid and 3% acetonitrile in water (v/v/v) (solvent A) and 0.1 % formic acid and 10% water in acetonitrile (v/v/v) (solvent B) was as follows: 0-16% B from 0-2 min; 16-100% B from 2-3 min; 100% B from 3-4.5 min; 100-0% B 4.5-5 min. The column was equilibrated with 100% A for 8 min before the next injection. MRM analysis was conducted in the positive mode with one transition as the quantifier and two transitions as qualifiers for the analyte and the internal standard. For glutathione, the quantifier was m/z 308.0 -> 179.0, and the qualifiers were m/z 308.0 -> 233.0 and m/z 308.0 -> 162.0. For glutathione-(glycine-13C2, 15N), the quantifier was m/z 311.0 -> 182.0, and the qualifiers were m/z 311.0 -> 165.0 and m/z 311.0 -> 84.0. Calibration standards of glutathione with a concentration range of 0.1-50 μg/mL and 2 μg/mL of internal standard were prepared in 20 mM DTT.
